ups. Part II offers a unique and rare insight into the correlates, causes, and contextual properties of domestic violence. Part III, which constitutes the substance of this book, explains how criminal justice systems--through their policies, procedures, and operations--respond to domestic violence. Following in the tradition of the first edition, this book devotes considerable attention to the experiences and perspectives of criminal and social justice practitioners alongside researchers, child welfare workers, and other renowned scholars across disciplines. Offering comprehensive and interdisciplinary coverage of key topics that benefit a diverse audience, the book concludes by offering a unique perspective on punishing and rehabilitating offenders"--Provided by publisher.0 aPrint version record.  a44 0aFamily violencevCross-cultural studies. 0aFamily violencexLaw and legislationzUnited States.1 aRoss, Lee E.,d1958-eeditor.403University of Alberta Accessuhttp://search.ebscohost.com/login.aspx?direct=true&scope=site&db=nlebk&db=nlabk&AN=802184z(Single User Access)  wORDERhUAINzPDACOUTTS  aInternet AccesswLCc1i6783884-1001lINTERNETmUAINTERNETrYsYtE-RESOURCEu1/16/2015xE-BOOKzPDAOWNED01ahttp://id.loc.gov/authorities/names/n97126340bhttp://viaf.org/viaf/28824439